Or/and add an educational on-ramp for users in coding agents themselves. To oversimplify: current frontier AIs are good enough at coding and good enough at talking and explaining, why not use both? 

Ideally you'd want a coding agent to be able to:

a) model the user and user's knowledge gaps (or contours of one or two large gaps (domain knowledge/implementation expertise)),

b) not be overfit to execute and supersede expectations (probably won't happen anytime soon with current focus on benchmarks etc in training) (until somebody propagates a mantra of precise execution and underengineering as a virtue)

c) play three and a half roles of: 
- project manager who negotiates with a "crazy/clueless" user and runs a domain knowledge communication loop and documents things; 
- developer that executes; 
- devops engineer that will deploy it; 
- all while explaining to the clueless user what is going on and why, identifying critical junctions in execution flow and asking for user input in user-legible (not even domain, let alone implementation-specific) language. 

I feel like something like this will be fixed when the tutoring aspect of AIs will be better developed. Creating something like this right now is possible but still very engineering-knowledge skewed. Or maybe it's a good "startup" idea, who knows. In any case, it feels to me like it's a waypoint towards agentic autonomy and closing the execution loop, and we're not there yet, but maybe soon-ish™.

